                    <span>This book epitomises so much of what is wrong in the software industry that I wonder if, in a sick kind of ironic way, that this is its only value?<P>It cashes in on buzzwords in the title but is full of errors and demonstrates a complete lack of understanding of the material by the author.<P>There is nothing to redeem this book. It is an embarassment.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">A book of extraordinarily low value</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>13</span>
                      /
                      <span>15</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>1999-06-07</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Around three years ago, I joked with a collegue of mine that a sure way to make a fortune would be to write a book which included the words "Java" and "Patterns" in the title. It would matter little, I argued, what the book contained. Just the title and a half-decent graphic on the front page would suffice.<P>It seems to me that both Mr Grand and his publishers Wiley are attempting to cash in on this very idea. The problem is that the joke was a bad one in the first place, and that it is now being made far too late in the day. <P>I hope that the software development community is sufficiently aware that it won't be taken in by this outrage.</span>
                  
              
